However, there are issues with the durability of identity.  In the
example of the court case, the URI that identifies &quot;the bank account
of some person currently using a user agent&quot; is not very useful.  Even
the bank couldn&#39;t tell whose account that was based only on the URI.

Walden

----- Original Message ----- 
From: &quot;Mark Baker&quot; &lt;distobj@...&gt;
To: &quot;Vincent D Murphy&quot; &lt;vdm@...&gt;
Cc: &quot;Tyler Close&quot; &lt;tyler@...&gt;; &lt;rest-discuss@yahoogroups.com&gt;
Sent: Wednesday, July 02, 2003 10:52 AM
Subject: [rest-discuss] URIs are RESTful


&gt; On Tue, Jul 01, 2003 at 10:02:16PM +0100, Vincent D Murphy wrote:
&gt; &gt; On Tuesday, Jul 1, 2003, at 19:56 Europe/Dublin, Tyler Close wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt; I am arguing against URIs like
&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;http://www.acmebank.com/accounts/current/12/&gt;, where this URI
&gt; &gt; &gt; refers the 12th most recent payment made by a particular user.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; ah.  thanks for that clarification.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; i think your point (that such URIs are RESTless) can be more
&gt; &gt; clearly made by stating that the only way that the &#39;current&#39;
&gt; &gt; account alluded to in your URI can be dereferenced is by having
&gt; &gt; access to some server-side state, or a session.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; this of course is RESTless all by itself because the server has
&gt; &gt; to maintain that state using a gross hack (cf. cookies).
&gt;
&gt; If it&#39;s a URI, then there&#39;s nothing at all RESTless about it.  That
&gt; URI is perfectly fine, even if what you GET from it differs depending
&gt; upon who invoked GET, the time of day, etc..  To say otherwise is
&gt; to prevent me from identifying a whole class of useful resources,
&gt; such as &quot;The person to my right&quot;, &quot;The colour of the next traffic
&gt; light up ahead&quot;, etc..
&gt;
&gt; Mark.
